title: Stress-test and fix thread pool when work queues are full
body:
**Description**: This PR addresses a case where the thread pool may drop work if all of the work queues are full.  The PR fixes the bug and adds a stress-test.  The new test previously failed, but now passes.

**Motivation and Context**
While investigating an unrelated issue, I noticed that the thread pool may drop tasks when a burst of 1024+ tasks is submitted by a thread from inside the pool.  Today, in general, we execute work synchronously in this case.  However, there is a bug where work submitted by a thread already inside the pool will be discarded instead of executed.  Currently the only scenario where I can see this occurring is when the parallel executor is used with a model in which such a large number of nodes become eligible to run all at once.  This PR fixes the underlying issue and adds a test case for burst-submission of work.

title: Revert "Remove code which is not thread-safe. (#4454)"
body:
This reverts commit 5222b2c6c0366033aaa78b95b2a0a49984984203.

We still need to log how much memory allocated for static initializers, static activation, and dynamic activation. The first commit brings that functionality back. This PR also make it thread-safe (it was removed because it wasn't thread-safe) by introducing a mutex in ExecutionFrame in https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/pull/4712/commits/4f163d23779399ad731b52e6f15a3d0b77e2c2d9 and some extra safety measures in https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/pull/4712/commits/78f8c518baf92b0ee01ba589e03a6594d25cb4ef.

From my preliminary investigation, the thread-safe is required because dynamic memory is logged in ExecutionFrame
```
  // Size of virtual memory allocated during kernel execution (i.e., inside a kernel,
  // we may allocate some memory for its outputs, if not planned.).
  // This field is not physical memory size.
  std::unordered_map<std::string, size_t> dynamic_activation_memory_sizes_in_byte_;
```
and parallel executor can launch multiple kernels at the same time (kernels can allocates dynamic memory at the same time).

With this PR and `--ort_log_severity 1`, we get information like below:
```
[Memory] SessionStateInitializer statically allocates 2386034688 bytes for Cuda
[Memory] SessionStateInitializer statically allocates 49152 bytes for Cpu
```
for constants and initializers and
```
[Memory] ExecutionFrame statically allocates 503553536 bytes for Cuda
[Memory] ExecutionFrame statically allocates 128 bytes for CudaPinned
[Memory] ExecutionFrame dynamically allocates 384 bytes for CudaPinned
[Memory] ExecutionFrame dynamically allocates 7296 bytes for Cuda
```
for activations.

title: Gradient Builder Supports FP16/BFloat16 and Transform Mixed Precision before Gradient Builder
body:
This PR includes:
- Refactor the mixed precision transformer to support other mixed precision data types other than FP16, only FP16 needs loss scale.
- Move mixed precision transformer before gradient builder, i.e., transform mixed precision on forward graph only.
- Add supporting mixed precision data types such as FP16/BFloat16 to gradient builder.
- Change Adam/Lamb optimizer to support more mixed precision data types other than FP16.

This PR is a preparation to support BFloat16 training. The target is to refactor the mixed precision transformer and gradient builder and make sure current FP32 and FP16 training works as usual. So it does NOT include any frontend parameter change or CUDA change to support new mixed precision data type (BFloat16).

More perf and correctness test results will be added here.

title: Add a generic collection of session configurations to the SessionOptions
body:
**Description**: 
Add generic configurations for session options

**Motivation and Context**
Right now in order to change some setting within an inference sessions, we will need to either
- Use ORTAPI, add entry if necessary, (will bloat the c/cxx_api)
- Use environmental variables, (not really work for some environments, such as mobile)
- Hardcode the settings (not really applicable to end users )

This proposal is to add a single function OrtApis::SetSessionConfiguration to add different configurations for the inference session
- Exposing new options will not require updating the ORTAPI any more
- Use a std::unordered_map as the collection of the configurations
- Define an enum as the config key, and a std::string as the config value, the consumer of the config will be responsible to parse the string
- EP will still using constructor for EP specific configurations

title: Optimize Slice Kernel by Removing If-statement
body:
Optimize Slice kernel performance by removing if-statement.

The issue was found in GPT2 model pretraining using spesific recipe, which contains a Slice/SliceGrad at the end of the model on a big tensor. Below table shows the nvprof result before and after this change.

Before, the Slice/SliceGrad takes half of the compute time in total:
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/11661208/89875894-6ae13700-dbf0-11ea-9359-a4c533fdde1b.png)

After, the compute time for the kernel is reduced significantly:
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/11661208/89875988-92d09a80-dbf0-11ea-9a89-b57f3d211243.png)

Perf test on single GPU using the GPT2 model above and batch size 32 also shows significant perf improvement:
- PT's throughput: 228.48
- ORT's throughput without this fix: 211.84
- ORT's throughput with this fix: 448.64

title: Open the door to use libtorch inside ORT
body:
Different kernel implementations sometimes very different results. This PR aims at providing flexibility to switch back to Pytorch code when debugging such issues. We basically

1. Add a flag to indicate the use of pytorch
2. Modify CMake files to build ORT with pytorch library
3. Add some helpers function to bridge ORT tensors and Pytorch tensors
4. Dispath MatMul to pytorch when USE_TORCH is set.
5. Create a test to use pytorch result as its baseline.

This PR doesn't make Pytorch a formal execution provider but shade some light in that direction.

Command to build ORT with Pytorch:
./build.sh --use_cuda --use_full_protobuf --config Debug  --build_wheel --enable_pybind --enable_training --enable_nvtx_profile --use_libtorch --libtorch_home /data/anaconda/envs/wechi37/lib/python3.7/site-packages/torch --use_openmp --parallel

Some exploration code can be found in #4687 and #4657.

title: Support RegisterCustomOpsLibrary via the Python API
body:
**Description**: `RegisterCustomOpsLibrary` is a mechanism via which custom kernels in shared libraries can be used to support a model containing ops not yet in the ONNX opset. This change supports it via the Python API.

There are some challenges associated with this:
1) Freeing `OrtCustomOpDomain`s associated with the custom kernels (https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/fdc5c308c4a579bcf96a170cffa3c00e761eb8cd/onnxruntime/test/testdata/custom_op_library/custom_op_library.cc#L120). Currently freeing is done by the user of C/C++ API via `OrtReleaseCustomOpDomain()`. In Python, just like in C/C++, we rely on the implementer of the shared library to release the OrtCustomOpDomains created within it (i.e.) we don't take ownership and manage the resource for the user.

2) Unloading the shared library
Currently the user has to manually unload the library via the provided handle while using the C/C++ API.  In Python, we unload the library automatically (no action needed by the user) when the last session using the session options connected with the shared library goes out of scope.

TODO:
- [x] Update relevant documentation in the custom op md files

- [x] See how this plays with the shallow copy and the deep copying mechanism offered by the `copy` module (https://docs.python.org/3/library/copy.html). If we think it is unsafe to allow deep copying SessionOptions instances in Python (because they hold associated OrtCustomOpDomain pointers), explicit disallow it by overriding the method for now until we have support for it. Python aliases are okay and they are not copies. For example, `so1 = Sessionoptions() so2 = so1`. This only creates aliases to the same object and preserves the object until all the referenced aliases go out of scope and this is supported. 
EDIT: It seems like currently `SessionOptions` isn't picklable. We need to investigate which instance attribute is causing the pickling issue and solve that. (Not sure if we even want to support pickling given that it could lead to security concerns). But given that it is not pickable, nobody will be able to shallow copy (`copy.copy()`) or deep copy (`copy.deepcopy()`) SessionOptions using the copy module and hence there is no action required. 

CC: @wenbingl

**Motivation and Context**
Fix https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/3958

title: Honor allow_spinning at barrier at end of parallel sections
body:
**Description**: This PR means that when the thread pool is configured to spin, then we spin at the barrier at the end of parallel sections in the main thread, in addition to having workers spin waiting for work.  The change updates Barrier.h to take an additional boolean to select spin/block, and passes this in based on the thread pool configuration.  It adds an additional test case for barriers, although no problems were identified by the test case.

**Motivation and Context**
Issue identified while investigating remaining Eigen vs OpenMP differences in 1.4.  PR perf tested on Linux (WSL) and on Windows.  On WSL over 143 opset7-11 models, P50 improvement to Eigen at peak performance is 5% (i.e. 50% of models are above this), p90 is 10%.  At 4 threads, P50 is 2% and P90 is 5%.  Around 1-2% of models showed a regression in my initial results; I re-ran all of these and confirmed that this was experimental noise unrelated to the change.

title: Print Memory Requirements Before Real Allocation
body:
**Description**: Display activation memory needed for Large Models

When we tried to understand the gaps on memory usage for large models (that cannot fit on one single GPU), we always need to know how much memory planned for initializers (e.g. training parameters) and activations (e.g. intermediate tensors). 

Initializers memory can be easily got from either the initializer planner (that happens before any CUDA memory allocation), or inferred from the parameter counts based on our knowledge on memory consumption.

For activations, we don't have such information.  This PR did this by just simply trying to generate a memory pattern earlier (for example before the initializer CUDA memory allocation) at the "best efforts", then we print it out, even though it will potentially fail later. The "best efforts" means, we try, but not necessary succeed. In the case where training graph have dim_param values, we will not have a successful memory pattern generated here, this is expected.

#### Sample outputs as below:

> OrtMemoryInfo:[name:CudaPinned id:0 OrtMemType:-1 OrtAllocatorType:1 Device:[DeviceType:0 MemoryType:1 DeviceId:0]]Activation Peak: Allocated memory for activations, size: 1048576
> OrtMemoryInfo:[name:Cpu id:0 OrtMemType:0 OrtAllocatorType:1 Device:[DeviceType:0 MemoryType:0 DeviceId:0]]Activation Peak: Allocated memory for activations, size: 513806912
> OrtMemoryInfo:[name:Cuda id:3 OrtMemType:0 OrtAllocatorType:1 Device:[DeviceType:1 MemoryType:0 DeviceId:3]]Activation Peak: Allocated memory for activations, size: 1395579008


**Motivation and Context**
- Why is this change required? What problem does it solve?
- If it fixes an open issue, please link to the issue here.

title: Enable metadata and signature changes in graph transformers
body:
After applying all the graph transformations the metadata and signature could have changes
(e.g.: new outputs got added, or the outputs/inputs got renamed). Therefore the local
copies of metadata and signature, that InferenceSession administrated for faster lookup, has to be updated, what isn't done so far. This leads to inconsistencies between the InferenceSession and the *actual* graph. And results in problems like (#4689).

As the metadata/signature orignially are stored  using `SaveModelMetadata`, this should be called after resolving the transformed graph in `Initialize` as well. Therefore I made the `SaveModelMetadata` execution idempotent by clearing the vectors/maps before refilling them. (There might maybe a better solution for this, especially for my concrete implementation). 


**Motivation and Context**
As described in issue #4689, i had a problem with not being able to set new outputs inside a graph transformer. While further investigating my issue, i thought about generally enabeling metadata/signature changes for graph transformers (mainly adding/removing/renaming in- or output)

title: support Normalized_0_1 and Normalized_1_1
body:
This PR is to support to tensorize input when model specified NominalPixelRange metadata as Normalized_0_1 and Normalized_1_1.

[Related doc](https://github.com/onnx/onnx/blob/master/docs/MetadataProps.md).

Basically, when the model specified the input as Normalized_0_1 or Normalized_1_1, our pipeline to tensorize the image will normalized the data from [0, 255] to either [0, 1] or [-1, 1].

title: Detect whether the node has been inserted cast nodes twice
body:
(*Updated)
**Description**:
`insert_cast_transformer` needs to be aware of whether the node has been cast before.
1. Add a additional Cast node check in `ForceSingleNodeCPUFloat16ToFloat32` to avoid inserting the same Cast Node twice.
2. Create the Cast Node name by `GenerateNodeName` to prevent future regression.
3. Add a unit test.

However, if the models have been done by inserting Cast node, some models will have some room to optimize the graph. (Because `insert_cast_transformer` is the last step in `InferenceSession`)

For example, the model given in the issue will output two different graphs if running `InferenceSession` with `onnxrt.GraphOptimizationLevel.ORT_ENABLE_BASIC` twice.

**Motivation and Context**
Fix the issue: https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/4745
onnxruntime InferenceSession (inserted Cast nodes) twice will cause a name conflict. (Same Cast node name)

title: Allow multiple sessions to share an allocator, optimize constant folding memory usage, expose arena configs.
body:
**Description**: Allow multiple sessions to share an allocator and optimize constant folding memory usage. 

**Motivation and Context**
* While debugging a scenario that involved 6 models per inference request, I observed that the cpu allocator (and hence the underlying bfc arena) was created for each session which led to suboptimal usage of the arena. This PR allows sessions to share the same allocator.
* Moreover, every node iteration in constant folding created a brand new instance of the CPU EP (and hence arena). This scenario had a large number of nodes where CF was getting applied. This PR reuses the same CPU EP that was registered with the session to execute CF. Not sure why we'd to create a new CPU EP. 
* In addition to the above, increasing the initial chunk size 10 times reduced the overall memory consumption of the application by 38%.
